Synchronous programming in JavaScript involves executing code sequentially, meaning one part of your program must finish before another can begin. In contrast, asynchronous programming allows parts of a program to be executed concurrently or at separate times. This means that while one part is busy running, other parts of the program are still being processed.

Let's look at examples for each:

Synchronous Programming:
```javascript
// Here is an example of synchronous programming with console.log.
let message = "Hello, World!";
console.log(message);
```
In this example, the `console.log` function will not output anything until the end of the block of code where it's called. Therefore, there can be no other parts of the program running while this is in progress.

Asynchronous Programming:
```javascript
// Here is an example of asynchronous programming with fetch API.
let response = await fetch('https://api.example.com');
console.log(response);
```
In this case, the `fetch` method returns a Promise that resolves when the request has been completed. The Promise can be awaited to get the result. So while the promise is being resolved, other parts of your program can still run.

In summary, synchronous programming ensures that each part of your code must wait for its predecessor before moving on, which means if something happens that causes one part of your code to take longer than expected, it can potentially cause a delay in your whole program until the slow part is finished. On the other hand, asynchronous programming allows parts of your program to run independently of each other, which can improve efficiency and responsiveness.

